#: ../../B/Bad-Thing.rst:5
msgid "Bad Thing"
msgstr "Bad Thing"

#: ../../B/Bad-Thing.rst:7
msgid "n\\."
msgstr "名詞"

#: ../../B/Bad-Thing.rst:9
msgid ""
"[very common; always pronounced as if capitalized. Orig. fr. the 1930 Sellar"
" & Yeatman parody of British history *1066 And All That*\\, but well-"
"established among hackers in the U.S. as well.] Something that can't "
"possibly result in improvement of the subject. This term is always "
"capitalized, as in \"Replacing all of the DSL links with bicycle couriers "
"would be a Bad Thing\". Oppose :ref:`Good-Thing`\\. British correspondents "
"confirm that :ref:`Bad-Thing` and :ref:`Good-Thing` (and prob. therefore "
":ref:`Right-Thing` and :ref:`Wrong-Thing`\\) come from the book referenced "
"in the etymology, which discusses rulers who were Good Kings but Bad Things."
" This has apparently created a mainstream idiom on the British side of the "
"pond. It is very common among American hackers, but not in mainstream usage "
"in the U.S. Compare :ref:`Bad-and-Wrong`\\."
msgstr ""
"[非常に一般的。常に大文字で始まるかのように発音される。元はSellarとYeatmanによる1930年の英国史パロディ\\ *1066 And All"
" That*\\ "
"に由来するが、米国のハッカーの間でもよく定着している]対象の改善につながりようがない何か。この用語は常に大文字で始める。たとえば「すべてのDSL回線を自転車便に置き換えるのはBad"
" Thingだろう」のように。\\ :ref:`Good-Thing`\\ と対をなす。英国の通信員によれば、\\ :ref:`Bad-Thing`\\"
" と\\ :ref:`Good-Thing`\\ (そしておそらくそれゆえ\\ :ref:`Right-Thing`\\ と\\ "
":ref:`Wrong-Thing`\\ )は語源にある本に由来し、その本は、Good King(良き王)だがBad "
"Thing(悪しき事)であった統治者たちを論じている。これはどうやら英国側で一般的な慣用句を生んだようだ。米国のハッカーの間では非常に一般的だが、米国の一般的な用法ではない。\\"
" :ref:`Bad-and-Wrong`\\ と比較せよ。"
